<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-355-934  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 355 934.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommuting Review: the Gordon Report  June 1 1989 v6 n6 p11(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Labor economist cites growing employer need for flexible staffingand pros-cons of different ways to achieve it. (Richard Belous)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Rules in employee-employer relationships are changing rapidly.andO;When employers look for more flexibility, staffing, pay, benefits,and terms of employment become more varied.andP;  Dr. Richard Belous ofthe National Planning Association at the Society for Work Optionsnotes that one way employers can achieve flexible scheduling is toexpand the number of contingent workers and use the hire-rehirecycle.andP;  Another method is by achieving more flexibility in thefull-time or permanent workers, in which a portion of wages are atrisk, based on how well the firm does.andP;  Contingent staffing hasbecome more important in a world economy with more competitionbecause there is more pressure on profits.andP;  Contingent workers arecheaper because they earn less money than full-time workers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FlextimeProfitCompetitionHiringPart-Time EmploymentManpower PlanningNational Planning Association.andO;Person:    Belous, Richard (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>